  "title": "Child Maltreatment Fatalities: Predicting Rates and the Efficacy of Child Welfare Policy",
  "abstract": "Scientists have studied child maltreatment fatalities (CMFs) for several decades, yet little research has examined the social context in which CMFs occur and whether prevention efforts are effective. Using state-level data from 2006–2008, we examine the social context in which CMFs occur and conduct a five-year follow-up to a study that found media attention predicted CMF-related legislation (Douglas, 2009 Douglas, E. M. 2009. Media coverage of child maltreatment fatalities: Does it result in state legislative change intended to prevent future fatalities?. Journal of Policy Practice, 8(3): 224–239. [Taylor & Francis Online] , [Google Scholar]). The results indicate that the social context in which children live are important; poverty and region are the strongest predictors of CMFs and states that passed legislation to prevent future maltreatment fatalities did not experience a decline in the death rate. Implications for policy and practice are discussed.",
